00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:59.420
We at Radcliffe are
especially proud of events

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:03.560
like this one, which cut
across traditional disciplines

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:07.970
to wrestle with complex
issues of public importance.

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:11.840
To understand the dynamics and
challenges of the US health

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:15.380
system, we have to
understand the interplay

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:21.130
of history, politics, economics,
science, and medicine.

00:01:21.130 --> 00:01:24.130
Today's distinguished
panelists bring a wide range

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:27.670
of expertise in these areas,
and I am grateful to them

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:31.090
for taking the time to be
with us this afternoon.

00:01:31.090 --> 00:01:34.990
Our discussion feels
especially important in light

00:01:34.990 --> 00:01:37.960
of the health impact
of natural disasters

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:39.880
like hurricane
Harvey and hurricane

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:43.870
Irma, which left hundreds
if not thousands in need

00:01:43.870 --> 00:01:47.290
of urgent medical attention
and could lead to longer

00:01:47.290 --> 00:01:50.770
term public health challenges.

00:01:50.770 --> 00:01:53.350
Today's conference also
marks the beginning

00:01:53.350 --> 00:01:55.720
of Radcliffe's two
year initiative

00:01:55.720 --> 00:02:00.220
on citizenship, which is
motivated in part by our desire

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:04.480
to contextualize the upcoming
100th anniversary of American

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:07.180
Women's Suffrage in 2020.

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:09.250
This discussion
today is the first

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:12.310
of many we are planning
over the next two years

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:17.140
to delve into different aspects
of what citizenship entails,

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:21.370
how it is defined,
and who can claim it.

00:02:21.370 --> 00:02:25.030
As today's title suggests,
here in the United States,

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:28.660
citizenship can be
especially complicated,

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:33.160
with benefits and obligations
that vary from one state

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:34.210
to another.

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:39.030
It really does depend
on what state you're in.

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:41.970
Since the nation's
independence Americans

00:02:41.970 --> 00:02:46.350
have struggled to find and
have often fiercely disagreed

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:51.040
over the appropriate balance
between federal, state,

00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:52.800
and local government.

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.340
This tension has broad
implications for policy

00:02:56.340 --> 00:02:59.190
and it has proved
an important factor

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:03.300
in the intense current
debate over health care.

00:03:03.300 --> 00:03:06.270
For much of the 19th
century, United States

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:09.360
had a relatively weak
central government

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:12.840
and a more powerful state
and local government.

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:15.870
Geography often
determine people's access

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:19.230
to public resources and the
extent to which government

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:21.790
protected individual rights.

00:03:21.790 --> 00:03:24.750
In other words, the
benefits of citizenship

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:30.840
very much depended on where in
the United States you lived.

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:32.790
Beginning with the
progressive movement

00:03:32.790 --> 00:03:36.000
at the turn of the 20th
century, the federal government

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.810
started to take on a
larger role in addressing

00:03:39.810 --> 00:03:42.660
economic and social problems.

00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:46.290
Congress passed the Pure
Food and Drug Act in 1906,

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.920
and other new nationwide
standards quickly followed.

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:53.250
The New Deal in the
1930s, the emergence

00:03:53.250 --> 00:03:57.000
of the Cold War security
state after World War II,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.760
and the Great Society
programs of the 1960s,

00:04:00.760 --> 00:04:02.700
which for today's
purposes, notably

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:04.950
created Medicare and Medicaid.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:10.170
Each marked further expansion of
the federal government's role.

00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:12.570
Although states
maintained responsibility

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:16.200
for implementation of
many federal programs,

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:20.550
uniformity across
state lines increased.

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:25.290
Then, in the early 1970s,
President Richard Nixon's

00:04:25.290 --> 00:04:29.790
"new federalism" began to
reverse the trend by increasing

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.430
state and local control.

00:04:32.430 --> 00:04:36.330
New federalism's block grants
gave states broad discretion

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:38.350
over social spending.

00:04:38.350 --> 00:04:42.210
This is particularly relevant
to our discussion today.

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:46.380
For example, earlier this
year several top Republican

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:50.070
lawmakers, including speaker
of the House Paul Ryan

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:53.430
articulated a vision
for converting Medicaid

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:56.700
to a federal block
grant program.

00:04:56.700 --> 00:05:00.840
The shift beginning in the
1970s towards dismantling

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:04.500
federal authority in
favor of state discretion

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:07.950
did not belong to any
one political party

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:09.900
in the years since Nixon.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:12.180
Jimmy Carter did his part.

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:15.480
Ronald Reagan ferociously
attacked federally funded

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:16.620
programs.

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:22.020
And Bill Clinton's 1996 welfare
reform replaced the New Deal

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:24.240
era Aid to Families
with Dependent Children

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:28.130
Program with a Temporary
Assistance to Needy Families,

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:30.690
or the TANF block grants.

00:05:30.690 --> 00:05:33.300
The result, for
better or worse, has

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:36.690
been declining federal
control over the social safety

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:39.540
net for almost a half century.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:44.250
And in turn, dramatic variation
in benefits and eligibility

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:47.730
requirements from
state to state.

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:52.410
These stark differences can be
seen in how each state chooses

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:54.930
to allocate TANF funds.

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:59.670
South Dakota spends
61% on cash assistance.

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.520
Texas spends 7%.

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:05.940
And each state sets
its own lifetime limit

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:07.620
on TANF benefits.

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:11.040
Here in Massachusetts,
the cap is five years.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:13.830
In Arizona it is 12 months.

00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:16.530
The Affordable
Care Act, which we

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:19.500
refer to as the
ACA, or Obamacare,

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:22.710
is very much a part
of this history.

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:26.910
When the ACA passed in
2010, it dramatically

00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:29.250
expanded the federal
government's role

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:31.410
in regulating both
the health insurance

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:36.120
industry and individual
choices about health coverage.

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:38.520
At the same time,
the ACA's design,

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:41.850
and much of the debate
before and after its launch,

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:44.910
has clearly reflected
deep disagreements

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:48.990
over the extent of state
versus federal authority, which

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:51.240
has been a part of
American politics

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:53.940
since the nation's
establishment.

00:06:53.940 --> 00:06:55.650
With all of this
history in mind,

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:57.300
and I am an historian
so I can't think

00:06:57.300 --> 00:06:59.430
about the problem
any other way, I

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:01.920
look forward to learning
more with you today

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.580
about the debates that are
still swirling around Obamacare

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:08.200
and the future prospects for
health care in the United

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:09.510
States.

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:12.690
So to get our afternoon started,
I would now like to hand things

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:15.540
over to Professor Dan Carpenter.

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:18.840
Dan is the Faculty Director
of the Social Sciences Program

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.600
at the Radcliffe Institute,
the Allie S. Freed Professor

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.330
of Government in the faculty
of Arts and Sciences,

00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:27.420
and the co-organizer with
Professor Janet RichEdwards

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:29.340
of today's symposium.

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:31.950
Please join me in welcoming
Dan to the podium.

00:07:42.530 --> 00:07:45.260
- Thank you Liz, and
welcome everybody

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:48.020
to the Radcliffe Institute.

00:07:48.020 --> 00:07:52.370
It seems just a short
while ago, but so long ago

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:55.370
that the United States entered
a heated, what at the time

00:07:55.370 --> 00:08:01.040
seemed interminable, battle over
what is now known as Obamacare.

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.590
Obamacare, the ACA,
seems like a settled

00:08:03.590 --> 00:08:06.989
fact in some discussions,
but it is not.

00:08:06.989 --> 00:08:08.780
And in case you forgot,
here's a few things

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:12.800
that happened in 2009, 2010.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:14.990
There was a bill in the
House of Representatives

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:17.270
that passed that
chamber with what

00:08:17.270 --> 00:08:20.990
was called a public option,
namely the ability of consumers

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:23.540
to choose a Medicare like
plan as part of their health

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:25.820
insurance plan menu.

00:08:25.820 --> 00:08:29.450
There was the refusal by Senator
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:31.550
to support that public option.

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:33.770
Which, given his pivotal
status in the Senate

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:37.820
at the time as the Democratic
Party's 60th coalition voter,

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:39.970
killed that plan.

00:08:39.970 --> 00:08:42.559
There was the passage of a
different Affordable Care Act

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:44.900
by the US Senate.

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:48.920
There was, as residents of
this state may remember,

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:51.920
the unexpected electoral
victory of Senator Scott

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:53.960
Brown in January 2010.

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:56.090
Which seemed, at
the time, according

00:08:56.090 --> 00:08:59.570
to many prognosticators,
to kill the whole effort.

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:01.900
There were the efforts
after that by speaker

00:09:01.900 --> 00:09:05.350
Nancy Pelosi to resurrect
the bill that had previously

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:09.040
passed the Senate in the
House of Representatives,

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:12.220
successfully through the
house, and on to President

00:09:12.220 --> 00:09:15.190
Obama for his signature.

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:18.790
There was the botched
rollout of the ACA website

00:09:18.790 --> 00:09:21.070
by the US federal government.

00:09:21.070 --> 00:09:23.170
There were the massive
Republican gains

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:26.250
in the midterms of 2010.

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:28.350
There was the first
Supreme Court case

00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:31.830
on the ACA, NFIB
versus Sebelius,

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:34.390
which upheld the
law by a thread,

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:36.600
and which gave states
the right to opt out

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:39.140
of Medicare expansion.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:42.170
And then there was a
second, not only the only,

00:09:42.170 --> 00:09:45.680
but a second Supreme Court
case on the ACA, King

00:09:45.680 --> 00:09:47.900
versus Burwell, which,
to put it simply,

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:50.530
upheld the law's subsidies.

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:53.497
Any one of these hurdles,
and there were many others,

00:09:53.497 --> 00:09:54.580
could have tripped up the.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:56.560
ACA.

00:09:56.560 --> 00:09:59.430
And now we too
easily regard the ACA

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:04.110
as part of a status quo, albeit
admittedly an unsettled one.

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:06.360
Today, the architecture
of the Affordable Care Act

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:09.870
has done some amazing things, as
we'll hear from our panelists.

00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:11.340
The percentage of
American adults

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:16.500
who lack health insurance
has fallen to historic lows.

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:19.440
Today's symposium will show the
politics of health insurance

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:23.400
have everything to do with
the ACA's achievements

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.090
and limitations.

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:27.540
Health insurance systems
depend as much, maybe m

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:29.400
upon political
institutions as they

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:33.630
do upon market characteristics
and system design.

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:37.740
The ACA is today under
attack on two fronts.

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:40.050
The first is probably
better known.

00:10:40.050 --> 00:10:42.540
The day after the
November 2016 election,

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:45.600
I predicted to my students
in a bureaucratic politics

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:49.050
class at Harvard, that
the ACA would be repealed.

00:10:49.050 --> 00:10:51.390
The Republicans
simply had to do it,

00:10:51.390 --> 00:10:54.850
I reasoned, as it had been
their mantra for eight years.

00:10:54.850 --> 00:10:57.570
And for now, I am wrong
in that prediction,

00:10:57.570 --> 00:11:00.150
and I hope I remain so.

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:03.300
Yet Repeal and Replace, with
its ever larger estimates

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:05.220
of those who will
lose health insurance,

00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:07.560
may still pass at some level.

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:09.090
And of course, the
federal subsidies

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:10.639
undergirding
regional marketplaces

00:11:10.639 --> 00:11:12.930
are in jeopardy as well from
the decisions of the Trump

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:14.790
administration.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:16.410
Today's first
panel will describe

00:11:16.410 --> 00:11:19.080
some of the politics that
went into the ACA, which

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:22.140
both sustains and
undermines that law,

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:26.370
but there remain often
largely invisible to us.

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:29.200
The other attack on the
status quo, comes if you will,

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:31.020
from the left.

00:11:31.020 --> 00:11:33.300
California's ongoing
legislative attempt

00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:34.860
to create a single
payer system has

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:37.200
gone the furthest in terms
of legislative progress

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:38.300
toward that end.

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:42.430
And we will hear about that
effort in today's second panel.

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:44.790
And of course, this past
week Senator Bernie Sanders

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:48.120
of Vermont unveiled his
Medicare for all proposal.

00:11:48.120 --> 00:11:51.090
Just as important, an
unexpectedly large number

00:11:51.090 --> 00:11:54.180
of Democrats, including senators
and presidential hopefuls

00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:58.020
for the 2020 contest have
now signed on as co-sponsors

00:11:58.020 --> 00:12:00.180
to Senator Sanders measure.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:04.010
So much so that some
are describing Medicare

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:06.380
for All, or another
version of single payer,

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:09.260
as a new litmus test for
the upcoming democratic

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:11.180
presidential primaries.

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:13.400
We shall see.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:15.710
There are, it is worth
noting, potential tensions

00:12:15.710 --> 00:12:19.130
between California's plan
and the Sanders' plan.

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:21.560
But clear momentum is
evident for some form

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:24.950
of universal government
sponsored health insurance.

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:26.960
Today's second panel
will demonstrate

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:29.270
that alternative
models for health care

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:31.610
are incredibly
diverse and force us

00:12:31.610 --> 00:12:35.360
to confront immense
tradeoffs and challenges.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:39.330
Single payer has
no single meaning

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:41.540
in exactly how it
is designed, which

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:43.550
means exactly how
it is politically

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:47.300
shaped means everything.

