00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:46.544
And so I thought to lay
the groundwork a little bit

00:14:46.544 --> 00:14:48.460
for the discussion
that will follow,

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:50.590
I'm going to describe
some of those key findings

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:53.800
in terms of what is working
and what isn't working.

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:56.410
Dan already mentioned
that the single highest

00:14:56.410 --> 00:14:58.030
item on the list
of what is working

00:14:58.030 --> 00:15:00.196
is that the Affordable Care
Act has been the largest

00:15:00.196 --> 00:15:02.290
expansion of health
insurance in over 50 years

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:04.900
and has brought the rate of the
uninsured population in the US

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:07.399
to the lowest it's been since
the federal government started

00:15:07.399 --> 00:15:08.394
tracking this number.

00:15:08.394 --> 00:15:10.810
Roughly 20 million Americans
have gained health insurance,

00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:12.880
primarily through
three mechanisms.

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:16.240
One is the expansion of Medicaid
to low income populations

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:18.730
who traditionally didn't
qualify for Medicaid.

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:21.730
And that's only been adopted in
31 states plus Washington, DC

00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:24.410
since the Supreme Court
made that an option.

00:15:24.410 --> 00:15:26.380
There's also the health
insurance marketplaces

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:29.541
that offer private insurance,
subsidized based on income,

00:15:29.541 --> 00:15:31.540
where people get tax
credits to help them afford

00:15:31.540 --> 00:15:33.460
private insurance
if they don't get

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:35.000
health insurance through work.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.150
And then finally for young
adults up through age 26

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:39.430
they're able to stay on
their parents' plans, which

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:41.830
was not generally available
prior to the Affordable Care

00:15:41.830 --> 00:15:42.850
Act.

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.210
Now what has that
coverage meant for people?

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.650
In a series of studies
that have been conducted

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.570
using a variety of
data sources, we

00:15:49.570 --> 00:15:52.180
can really get a picture of
what this health insurance

00:15:52.180 --> 00:15:54.190
expansion means for people.

00:15:54.190 --> 00:15:57.160
First off when you look at
just broad national trends

00:15:57.160 --> 00:15:59.920
and national surveys, you see
that as coverage has expanded,

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:02.170
fewer Americans have said
they can't get the care they

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:03.922
need because of affordability.

00:16:03.922 --> 00:16:05.380
They can afford
the care they need.

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:07.654
They're more likely to have
a source of primary care.

00:16:07.654 --> 00:16:09.070
They're more likely
to have access

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:10.900
to medications that they need.

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:13.450
If you look at prescription
claims that are filled,

00:16:13.450 --> 00:16:15.610
we see increases,
particularly in states

00:16:15.610 --> 00:16:17.500
that have expanded
Medicaid, in coverage

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:20.620
for drugs that are important
for chronic disease management,

00:16:20.620 --> 00:16:24.010
things like diabetes and heart
disease and mental illness.

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:26.340
We also see improvements
in how people feel.

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:28.326
We actually, in
several studies, have

00:16:28.326 --> 00:16:30.700
found that the expansion of
coverage under the Affordable

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:32.800
Care Act has lead patients
to rate their health

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:34.156
as having improved.

00:16:34.156 --> 00:16:35.530
And again, the
strongest evidence

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:37.824
has been from the study
of Medicaid expansion.

00:16:37.824 --> 00:16:40.240
Now why has so much evidence
been produced on the Medicaid

00:16:40.240 --> 00:16:41.230
expansion?

00:16:41.230 --> 00:16:42.610
We have a natural experiment.

00:16:42.610 --> 00:16:46.280
Since it is up to each state, we
have 32 examples of expansions

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:47.867
and 19 nonexpansions.

00:16:47.867 --> 00:16:49.450
And those comparisons
have been really

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:51.460
valuable in letting
us understand

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.440
what's at stake with
these coverage gains

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:55.750
and what it means
for people's lives.

00:16:55.750 --> 00:16:58.630
Now what hasn't worked as
well-- and I could go on

00:16:58.630 --> 00:17:02.020
much longer about how this
coverage means benefits

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:02.790
to people's lives.

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:05.754
But in terms of thinking about
the dysfunctions of the ACA,

00:17:05.754 --> 00:17:07.670
there are a couple of
points I'd like to make.

00:17:07.670 --> 00:17:10.450
The first is what many of
you have probably heard about

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:13.780
in the lay media, which is the
notion that the marketplaces

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:15.819
are not stable and that
they are collapsing--

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:18.819
as our president often says--

00:17:18.819 --> 00:17:21.609
has a kernel of truth
to it and mostly a lot

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:23.849
of rhetorical exaggeration.

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:26.140
So what we know is that the
marketplaces have generally

00:17:26.140 --> 00:17:28.390
been stable in most
parts of the country.

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:30.100
But there are areas
in the country

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:33.160
where there are only one or
two insurers participating.

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:35.350
That has implications in
terms of higher premiums,

00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:37.600
and it also means that people
have fewer choices when

00:17:37.600 --> 00:17:38.650
they're shopping.

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:40.240
That doesn't mean that they
don't have any coverage

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:41.020
options at all.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:43.450
And to date, even though there
have been some near misses,

00:17:43.450 --> 00:17:46.060
every county has ultimately
been able to offer insurance

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:48.580
to people on the marketplaces.

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:50.560
Now the coverage gained
through the marketplace

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:52.502
differs quite a bit
from the coverage people

00:17:52.502 --> 00:17:54.460
get through Medicaid, in
particular in the form

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:55.930
of higher cost sharing.

00:17:55.930 --> 00:17:58.889
The marketplace plans
typically feature deductibles

00:17:58.889 --> 00:18:00.430
that can be several
thousand dollars,

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:02.800
and the most commonly
chosen type of plan

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:06.160
is only, by law, supposed
to cover 70% of costs,

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:08.380
meaning people pay
30% out-of-pocket.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:10.750
Lower income people do
get some subsidies to help

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.289
that become more affordable.

00:18:12.289 --> 00:18:14.080
But clearly this still
leaves some barriers

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:16.160
in affordability
for many people.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:18.070
And so how do you
square these two pieces

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:19.070
of what I just told you?

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:20.611
Well, the first is
talking about what

00:18:20.611 --> 00:18:24.160
has the ACA done compared to
the status quo prior to the law?

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:25.690
The second is that
there are still

00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:28.540
significant areas of concern
and significant barriers

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:30.850
for some people under
the Affordable Care Act.

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:32.374
Now even more
notable than the fact

00:18:32.374 --> 00:18:33.790
that some people
who have coverage

00:18:33.790 --> 00:18:36.100
that isn't quite
affordable is we also

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:38.964
have 3 to 4 million low
income adults in the 19 states

00:18:38.964 --> 00:18:40.630
that have chosen not
to expand Medicaid,

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:42.340
and they simply have
no affordable option

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:43.850
for health insurance.

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:45.940
And if you think about
state-by-state variation,

00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:47.481
it's illustrative
to know that if you

00:18:47.481 --> 00:18:51.220
are a single parent in Texas,
your income has to actually

00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:55.060
be under $6,000 a year,
as an approximate,

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:56.170
to qualify for Medicaid.

00:18:56.170 --> 00:18:58.570
If you're earning $7,000 or
$8,000 as a single parent

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:01.120
you are too rich, in
many cases, for coverage.

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:02.850
If you have no
children in your home,

00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:04.450
it does not matter
how poor you are.

00:19:04.450 --> 00:19:07.450
Unless you have a disability,
you won't qualify for Medicaid.

00:19:07.450 --> 00:19:09.580
Now beyond the choices
of Medicaid expansion,

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:11.540
the broadest dysfunction
that some people

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:13.430
view in the Affordable
Care Act is simply

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:15.500
that even if it had
been fully implemented

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:19.400
without any challenges in the
courts and any state level

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:22.280
opposition, there still would
have been an estimated 20 to 25

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:24.571
million people without health
insurance when it was all

00:19:24.571 --> 00:19:25.230
said and done.

00:19:25.230 --> 00:19:28.250
The ACA was never intended
as a universal coverage bill.

00:19:28.250 --> 00:19:30.980
You might argue that that was
not a dysfunction of the ACA

00:19:30.980 --> 00:19:32.840
but a dysfunction of
the political system

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:35.000
or the realities of what
the political system was

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:36.890
able to produce given,
as Dan described,

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:39.732
how many near-death experiences
even this law went through.

00:19:39.732 --> 00:19:41.690
But that's where I think
the debate has shifted

00:19:41.690 --> 00:19:44.450
on the left in recent
months, which is not simply

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:47.540
trying to improve the ACA but
looking at the 20 to 30 million

00:19:47.540 --> 00:19:49.580
who don't really have
any prospect for coverage

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:51.690
even with a more
stable marketplace

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:54.512
and even if we can coax more
states into expanding Medicaid.

00:19:54.512 --> 00:19:56.720
So I look forward to discussing
these in more detail.

00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:57.830
And now I'm going
to turn it over

00:19:57.830 --> 00:19:59.900
to the first of our
panelists, Dr. Campbell.

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:02.732
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:08.304
- Well good afternoon everyone.

00:20:08.304 --> 00:20:09.720
I'm delighted to
be on this panel.

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:11.095
And many thanks
to the organizers

00:20:11.095 --> 00:20:13.520
for inviting me and thanks
to the Radcliffe leadership

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:15.590
and all the many people
it takes to put together

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:17.930
an event like this.

00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:20.150
As the political
scientist on the panel,

00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:23.270
I wish to focus on the theme of
citizenship, part of the larger

00:20:23.270 --> 00:20:25.070
initiative that
Radcliffe is undertaking

00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:27.590
for the next couple of
years, and in particular

00:20:27.590 --> 00:20:31.100
how public policies,
including the ACA,

00:20:31.100 --> 00:20:35.120
shape citizenship for Americans
and their ability, desire,

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:36.980
and likelihood that
they'll participate

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:40.040
in American governance,
because participation

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:44.070
is one of our fundamental duties
as citizens in a democracy.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:47.060
So I'll talk today about the
political effects of the ACA

00:20:47.060 --> 00:20:48.979
and the threats to the ACA.

00:20:48.979 --> 00:20:51.020
And in doing so, we're
going to take a brief walk

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:54.200
through some political science,
brief only, and then talk

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:56.870
about the implications
of the ACA.

00:20:56.870 --> 00:20:59.780
And in doing so I'm going
to use the lens of policy

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:02.000
feedbacks, which
is a perspective

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.880
within political science
that sees public policies

00:21:05.880 --> 00:21:09.560
not just as the outcomes
of political processes

00:21:09.560 --> 00:21:11.450
but also as inputs.

00:21:11.450 --> 00:21:14.540
That is that existing
public policies

00:21:14.540 --> 00:21:17.510
change the political environment
through their effects

00:21:17.510 --> 00:21:21.080
on budgets, through their
effects on ideas about what

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:24.830
good policy is, what
appears to work or not work,

00:21:24.830 --> 00:21:27.050
through their effects
on interest groups--

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:30.020
some interest groups are
elevated by public policies

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:33.410
or by a particular policy
while others are sidelined--

00:21:33.410 --> 00:21:35.240
and what I'll focus
on today which

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:38.690
are policies' effects
on ordinary citizens,

00:21:38.690 --> 00:21:43.550
because policies affect
people's views about government

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:47.480
and how effective it is and what
role it should play in society,

00:21:47.480 --> 00:21:49.340
and because policies
affect individuals

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:51.440
likelihood of participation
and their likelihood

00:21:51.440 --> 00:21:56.440
of participating in the face of
threat as we saw this summer.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:21:58.640
So what drives
political participation?

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:01.690
Well people are more likely
to vote, contact elected

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:05.170
officials, work on
campaigns, protest,

00:22:05.170 --> 00:22:08.290
go to town hall meetings,
make contributions

00:22:08.290 --> 00:22:12.340
when they want to, when
they're interested in doing so,

00:22:12.340 --> 00:22:15.250
and when someone has
asked them to do so.

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:17.470
That is, do they have
enough resources to get over

00:22:17.470 --> 00:22:20.740
the many humps and
hurdles in our society

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:22.780
to political participation?

00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:25.960
Are they engaged enough in
politics to make that effort?

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:29.880
And are they mobilized
to participate?

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:32.520
And public policies can shape
all three of these factors--

00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:35.640
resources, engagement,
and mobilization.

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:39.300
But whether policies have
these participatory effects

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:42.060
and whether those effects
are positive or negative

00:22:42.060 --> 00:22:44.320
depends on several factors.

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:46.830
The level of
resources they convey,

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:50.220
are they significant to get
people over those hurdles

00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:51.660
to participation?

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:54.100
Do they provide enough
financial security

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:56.040
so that people can
engage in politics, which

00:22:56.040 --> 00:23:00.460
is really a luxury activity?

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:03.580
The visibility of
government effort--

00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:05.950
can you even tell that you're
in a government program?

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:10.210
Some programs are more
submerged or hidden than others.

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:12.100
There's also the
issue of the messages

00:23:12.100 --> 00:23:15.100
that policy designs
send to citizens.

00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:17.020
Are recipients of
public policies or those

00:23:17.020 --> 00:23:18.730
on the receiving
end, are they treated

00:23:18.730 --> 00:23:22.720
respectfully and fairly, or
are they stigmatized or subject

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:26.420
to gatekeeping and to scrutiny?

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:29.180
And are there any entities
or information channels

00:23:29.180 --> 00:23:32.330
that are mobilizing people
around a policy area?

00:23:32.330 --> 00:23:34.550
Or perhaps in some
cases could a policy

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:37.760
be so important to people's
well-being they can, in a way,

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:40.190
self-mobilize?

00:23:40.190 --> 00:23:42.520
So let's consider the
politics of health reform,

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:44.320
the Affordable
Care Act, in light

00:23:44.320 --> 00:23:46.360
of these policy feedbacks.

00:23:46.360 --> 00:23:48.340
We saw this repeal
and replace effort,

00:23:48.340 --> 00:23:50.950
in particular the Republican's
American Health Care

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:54.520
Act of 2017, this
summer was defeated.

00:23:54.520 --> 00:23:57.940
We saw a groundswell of
political participation,

00:23:57.940 --> 00:24:01.570
of grassroots activity, which
exerted considerable pressure

00:24:01.570 --> 00:24:03.670
and played a major
role in pushing back

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:05.590
against this repeal effort.

00:24:05.590 --> 00:24:08.290
So what elements
of the ACA may have

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:10.690
helped spur this
participation, and what

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.420
are the prospects
for ACA's survival?

00:24:13.420 --> 00:24:16.610
Because as Dan noted,
it's an open question.

00:24:16.610 --> 00:24:18.700
So it's not at all
clear from the outset

00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:21.550
the ACA would have enhanced
political participation

00:24:21.550 --> 00:24:23.600
among the population.

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:25.090
First of all, as
you know, the ACA

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:30.790
was not all that popular
until the repeal effort.

00:24:30.790 --> 00:24:33.887
It was hovering under
a 50% approval rating.

00:24:33.887 --> 00:24:35.470
It was not at all
clear that Americans

00:24:35.470 --> 00:24:37.240
would rise to defend it.

00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:39.190
Supporters of the
law had always hoped

00:24:39.190 --> 00:24:41.200
that as people
experienced the benefits,

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:43.510
they would become
more supportive.

00:24:43.510 --> 00:24:46.840
But many beneficiaries felt
that health insurance was still

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:49.780
too expensive, even
after the reform.

00:24:49.780 --> 00:24:52.990
Those people who had
employer-based insurance

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:56.200
had a tendency to attribute
problems or premium increases

00:24:56.200 --> 00:24:59.470
in their insurance to the
ACA, with varying degrees

00:24:59.470 --> 00:25:01.520
of justification.

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:03.790
So there are some design
elements of the ACA

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:06.760
that might enhance
participation.

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:09.862
Many of the benefits in the
ACA went to the middle class,

00:25:09.862 --> 00:25:12.070
people who are more likely
to participate in politics

00:25:12.070 --> 00:25:15.250
who traditionally have more
voice than, say, lower income

00:25:15.250 --> 00:25:16.610
citizens.

00:25:16.610 --> 00:25:20.080
So for example, the subsidies
for those purchasing health

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:23.170
plans on the marketplaces,
those subsidies

00:25:23.170 --> 00:25:25.780
went far into the
middle class, up to 400%

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:28.450
of the poverty level,
which is around $88,000

00:25:28.450 --> 00:25:30.880
for a family of four.

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:33.040
The dependent care
provision, the provision

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:35.740
that allows children to stay on
their parents' health insurance

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:39.220
until age 26, that too is a
big help to the middle class

00:25:39.220 --> 00:25:40.780
and affluent, the
kinds of people who

00:25:40.780 --> 00:25:44.050
are most likely to have the
employer-based insurance

00:25:44.050 --> 00:25:46.690
to put their kids on.

00:25:46.690 --> 00:25:49.210
The ban on preexisting
condition exclusions--

00:25:49.210 --> 00:25:51.610
well that's a boon to
people of all income levels.

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:53.440
About a quarter of
Americans have some kind

00:25:53.440 --> 00:25:54.880
of preexisting condition.

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:57.340
And preexisting conditions
tend not to recognize

00:25:57.340 --> 00:25:59.560
the boundaries of income.

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:02.500
And other regulations, such as
the list of essential health

00:26:02.500 --> 00:26:04.880
benefits, also helps everyone.

00:26:04.880 --> 00:26:07.045
So there are quite a few
provisions in the ACA

00:26:07.045 --> 00:26:08.920
that were benefiting
people who traditionally

00:26:08.920 --> 00:26:11.950
have relatively more voice
in the political system,

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:14.080
middle class people,
upper income people,

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:18.060
more so than lower
income citizens.

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:20.160
On the other hand, there
were aspects of the ACA

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:23.340
that might serve to undermine
political participation

00:26:23.340 --> 00:26:30.746
or at least not boost it, either
because these provisions helped

00:26:30.746 --> 00:26:33.120
groups that traditionally
participate in politics at very

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:35.640
low rates or because
they were provisions that

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:38.680
were pretty hidden from view.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:41.680
So much of ACA's insurance
expansion, as you know,

00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:43.960
operated through the
expansion of Medicaid.

00:26:43.960 --> 00:26:45.720
But of course, it's
been mentioned,

00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:49.460
19 states decided not
to expand Medicaid.

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:52.510
And so that didn't boost the
pool of potential defenders

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:54.880
in that there.

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.340
Also, much of
Medicaid, including

00:26:57.340 --> 00:27:00.910
those who are newly eligible,
many of the aspects of it

00:27:00.910 --> 00:27:02.410
were pretty hidden.

00:27:02.410 --> 00:27:07.000
So some states, in an effort
in part to reduce stigma,

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.060
call their Medicaid program
something other than Medicaid.

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:13.330
Even here in Massachusetts,
it's MassHealth, right?

00:27:13.330 --> 00:27:15.190
In Oregon, there's the
Oregon Health Plan.

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:17.260
In Tennessee, there's TennCare.

00:27:17.260 --> 00:27:20.170
A number of states have
these alternative names.

00:27:20.170 --> 00:27:23.770
And studies show that in those
states with alternative names

00:27:23.770 --> 00:27:26.500
to Medicaid, there is
in fact less stigma

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:28.270
associated with Medicaid.

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:32.470
But also, people are less likely
to recognize their in Medicaid.

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:34.750
They're in something else.

00:27:34.750 --> 00:27:37.060
Another element
of program design

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:40.300
is that most states these
days require most Medicaid

00:27:40.300 --> 00:27:43.015
recipients to be in
a managed care plan

00:27:43.015 --> 00:27:46.150
in order to minimize costs,
you know, an HMO, PPO,

00:27:46.150 --> 00:27:48.110
some kind of managed care.

00:27:48.110 --> 00:27:49.810
So sometimes you get
an insurance card

00:27:49.810 --> 00:27:51.880
that still says Medicaid on it.

00:27:51.880 --> 00:27:53.470
But often you get
an insurance card

00:27:53.470 --> 00:27:56.140
that has the managed
care plan's name.

00:27:56.140 --> 00:27:58.510
And there again,
studies show that people

00:27:58.510 --> 00:28:01.330
with these insurance cards
that don't mention Medicaid

00:28:01.330 --> 00:28:03.820
are less likely to know
that they're in Medicaid.

00:28:03.820 --> 00:28:05.710
And they also
participate in politics

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:07.300
at lower rates than
people in states

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:09.760
where Medicaid insurance
cards still say Medicaid.

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:15.060
Another sort of
hidden aspect of ACA--

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:17.250
think about the
under 26 provision.

00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:19.380
Well, that helps the
middle class, as I noted.

00:28:19.380 --> 00:28:22.350
But young people themselves
tend to vote and participate

00:28:22.350 --> 00:28:24.510
in politics at pretty low rates.

00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:26.850
And work by political scientist
Jacqueline [INAUDIBLE],,

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:29.820
who got here PhD from here
in the Government department,

00:28:29.820 --> 00:28:33.300
shows that young people
who were newly covered,

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:35.670
newly got insurance
under this provision,

00:28:35.670 --> 00:28:37.890
were no more likely to
participate in politics

00:28:37.890 --> 00:28:41.020
afterwards than those who hadn't
been covered by this provision

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:44.230
or themselves earlier in life.

00:28:44.230 --> 00:28:47.300
So we had these sort
of two sets of factors,

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:48.990
some that might
enhance participation,

00:28:48.990 --> 00:28:50.700
some that might
undermine participation

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:52.110
or at least not boost it.

00:28:52.110 --> 00:28:53.970
It's not clear at
all what the balance

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:57.180
would be regarding the ACA.

00:28:57.180 --> 00:28:58.680
So far what we've found--

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:02.790
well, some scientists
have compared counties,

00:29:02.790 --> 00:29:04.680
comparing counties
at state borders

00:29:04.680 --> 00:29:07.320
where one side of
the border, the state

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:09.060
expanded Medicaid,
and the other side,

00:29:09.060 --> 00:29:10.710
the state did not
expand Medicaid.

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:13.600
But otherwise, those residents,
the local economy, et cetera,

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:15.000
is very, very similar.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.250
And they found a
mild positive effect,

00:29:17.250 --> 00:29:21.270
that those people on the
Medicaid expansion side

00:29:21.270 --> 00:29:24.720
were voting, doing voter turnout
at slightly higher rates.

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:27.210
And the effects were largest
in the poorest counties.

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:30.600
So that's a positive
effect of ACA.

00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:33.180
On the other hand, we also
know that ACA, as noted,

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:35.670
often provided health insurance
to low participation groups

00:29:35.670 --> 00:29:37.380
or in a hidden way.

00:29:37.380 --> 00:29:40.260
And there was a really
heartbreaking story by Sarah

00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:44.340
Kliff, the wonderful health
expert reporter, on Vox,

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:48.300
talking about Kentucky and its
health care exchange, kynect,

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:52.290
K-Y-N-E-C-T. So Kentucky had
a very high uninsurance rate

00:29:52.290 --> 00:29:53.580
before the ACA.

00:29:53.580 --> 00:29:57.120
It's the state that had the
biggest decline in uninsurance,

00:29:57.120 --> 00:30:01.740
because of kynect and
vigorous outreach efforts.

00:30:01.740 --> 00:30:02.907
But those outreach efforts--

00:30:02.907 --> 00:30:04.865
you know, this is a state
where a lot of people

00:30:04.865 --> 00:30:06.390
are skeptical about government.

00:30:06.390 --> 00:30:09.480
And when some people considering
signing up for insurance

00:30:09.480 --> 00:30:15.150
would approach navigators, they
would say, is this Obamacare?

00:30:15.150 --> 00:30:18.660
And the navigators would
say, no, no, it's kynect.

00:30:18.660 --> 00:30:20.765
And then when the
law is threatened,

00:30:20.765 --> 00:30:22.140
the same people
would say, oh, we

00:30:22.140 --> 00:30:23.940
don't have to worry
about Obamacare repeal

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:26.130
because we're in kynect.

00:30:26.130 --> 00:30:29.535
So there are downsides to hiding
the origin of these things.

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:35.060
Then came the Republicans
repeal effort.

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:40.750
And there's few forces with
as much mobilizing potential

00:30:40.750 --> 00:30:42.470
as threat.

00:30:42.470 --> 00:30:44.570
Psychologists have told
us about the asymmetry

00:30:44.570 --> 00:30:45.830
of gains and losses.

00:30:45.830 --> 00:30:48.320
It's very hard to take
something away from people.

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:53.030
People value losses more
than equal sized gains.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:57.230
And with the threat of repeal,
the popularity of the ACA

00:30:57.230 --> 00:30:58.280
finally rose.

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:01.070
It broke 50% for the first time.

00:31:01.070 --> 00:31:03.200
People turned out at
town hall meetings,

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:05.960
called congressional officers,
in general raised hell

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:09.080
and helped push back
the repeal effort.

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:12.620
And in threatening repeal,
Republicans essentially

00:31:12.620 --> 00:31:16.160
succeeded in making
the invisible visible,

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:18.120
two things in particular.

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:21.170
Much of the ACA works
through regulations.

00:31:21.170 --> 00:31:23.870
Think about the list of 10
essential health benefits.

00:31:23.870 --> 00:31:26.840
It's hard to appreciate that you
now have coverage for something

00:31:26.840 --> 00:31:28.881
that you didn't know you
didn't have coverage for

00:31:28.881 --> 00:31:33.980
before until it's
going to be taken away.

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:36.710
Medicaid-- Republicans
have wanted for decades

00:31:36.710 --> 00:31:39.260
to end the Medicaid entitlement.

00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:41.120
Medicaid is jointly
funded by the states

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:43.249
and the federal government.

00:31:43.249 --> 00:31:45.290
The federal government
sends its matching dollars

00:31:45.290 --> 00:31:48.080
to cover all the people
that states deem eligible.

00:31:48.080 --> 00:31:50.387
Republicans hate this.

00:31:50.387 --> 00:31:52.220
And I think it's because
in their proposals,

00:31:52.220 --> 00:31:54.110
they have a serious
misconception about who

00:31:54.110 --> 00:31:56.300
is in Medicaid.

00:31:56.300 --> 00:31:59.420
And the repeal threat
brought to the fore

00:31:59.420 --> 00:32:01.580
all these groups that
remind us there's

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:03.984
lots of people in
Medicaid who are not

00:32:03.984 --> 00:32:05.900
the people the Republicans
are thinking about.

00:32:05.900 --> 00:32:07.483
The republicans are
thinking that, oh,

00:32:07.483 --> 00:32:10.190
a lot of people in Medicaid
could, if they wanted to,

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.102
go out and get a job with
employer-provided insurance.

00:32:13.102 --> 00:32:14.810
Not so easy, because
some of those people

00:32:14.810 --> 00:32:16.100
literally can't work.

00:32:16.100 --> 00:32:17.725
And there are many
parts of the country

00:32:17.725 --> 00:32:19.895
where it's hard to get a
job with health insurance.

00:32:19.895 --> 00:32:21.520
When the threat came
along this summer,

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:25.190
we heard from all these
other groups within Medicaid,

00:32:25.190 --> 00:32:28.970
families with disabled elders,
former middle class people who

00:32:28.970 --> 00:32:30.440
had run through
all their resources

00:32:30.440 --> 00:32:33.230
and now need Medicaid to pay
their nursing home or home

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:36.140
health care, even
more potent, parents

00:32:36.140 --> 00:32:39.290
of disabled children, physically
or cognitively disabled

00:32:39.290 --> 00:32:42.200
children who are in Medicaid,
again, a lot of middle class

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:44.300
people who can't otherwise
afford their children's

00:32:44.300 --> 00:32:48.720
incredibly expensive care,
families of people seeking

00:32:48.720 --> 00:32:51.450
opioid addiction
treatment, again oftentimes

00:32:51.450 --> 00:32:54.510
middle class families who faced
a tragedy for which Medicaid

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:56.829
is a crucially important pair.

00:32:56.829 --> 00:32:59.370
And all of these people would
be harmed by Republican efforts

00:32:59.370 --> 00:33:01.770
to turn Medicaid
into a capped program

00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:04.910
and strip out $800
billion in funding.

00:33:04.910 --> 00:33:06.870
And who were the protesters--

00:33:06.870 --> 00:33:09.000
I'm happy to say-- at
Radcliffe Institute?

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.250
As Theda Skocpol has
pointed out, in many cases,

00:33:11.250 --> 00:33:15.510
it was women who organized and
rose up to fight the appeal,

00:33:15.510 --> 00:33:19.260
because women are still
disproportionately health care

00:33:19.260 --> 00:33:21.390
decision makers
in many families.

00:33:21.390 --> 00:33:23.940
They tend to be the
caretakers in families.

00:33:23.940 --> 00:33:29.080
And they're very aware of the
toll that repeal would impose.

00:33:29.080 --> 00:33:31.630
So I'll just close
with a few observations

00:33:31.630 --> 00:33:34.060
about prospects for the future.

00:33:34.060 --> 00:33:36.220
The fight is far from over.

00:33:36.220 --> 00:33:40.270
And now what concerns me is that
the current attacks on the ACA

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:44.020
are not the visible repeal
attacks from Congress.

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:46.930
They're the invisible
administrative attacks

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:49.930
from within the executive
branch, the defunding

00:33:49.930 --> 00:33:53.710
of navigators, the cessation
of advertising for those who

00:33:53.710 --> 00:33:56.230
might newly sign up this fall.

00:33:56.230 --> 00:33:58.330
They're sowing doubt
and uncertainty

00:33:58.330 --> 00:34:01.430
so insurers will pull
out of marketplaces.

00:34:01.430 --> 00:34:03.670
And my concern is
that the citizens who

00:34:03.670 --> 00:34:08.830
mobilized against the visible
repeal efforts this summer

00:34:08.830 --> 00:34:11.770
won't recognize or
know about or be

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:14.710
aware of these other
more insidious kinds

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:19.550
of administrative actions that
will be just as effective.

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:21.684
So that's what I'm really
concerned about now,

00:34:21.684 --> 00:34:23.350
is the nature of the
current dismantling

00:34:23.350 --> 00:34:25.210
being much more hidden
and not resulting

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:28.840
in action among the public.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:30.820
And then the very last
little normative comment

00:34:30.820 --> 00:34:34.300
I can't resist since someone
brought up federalism.

00:34:34.300 --> 00:34:36.670
I have a lot of colleagues
who study social policy

00:34:36.670 --> 00:34:37.750
in other countries.

00:34:37.750 --> 00:34:40.659
And they cannot believe that
in the United States you would

00:34:40.659 --> 00:34:44.650
have an uninsurance rate of
4% in Massachusetts and--

00:34:44.650 --> 00:34:48.889
well, now it's-- 18% in
Texas for the under 65 group.

00:34:48.889 --> 00:34:51.010
So think about all the
people in this room.

00:34:51.010 --> 00:34:53.469
A couple of hundred
people, right?

00:34:53.469 --> 00:34:55.780
Only 4%, 4 out of
100 of you would

00:34:55.780 --> 00:34:57.640
be without insurance
in Massachusetts.

00:34:57.640 --> 00:35:02.260
In Texas, it's one out of every
five people, you, and you,

00:35:02.260 --> 00:35:02.860
and you.

00:35:02.860 --> 00:35:05.740
I mean, it's a lot of people.

00:35:05.740 --> 00:35:07.830
What could such variation
possibly achieve?

00:35:07.830 --> 00:35:10.330
It raises a lot of questions
in our federal system, which is

00:35:10.330 --> 00:35:14.930
very useful in many, many ways.

00:35:14.930 --> 00:35:18.400
But this kind of variation,
is it responsive?

00:35:18.400 --> 00:35:19.840
Is it effective?

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:20.980
Is it moral?

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:22.710
So I will leave you
with those thoughts

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:24.920
and look forward to my
fellow panelists' comments.

00:35:24.920 --> 00:35:25.708
Thank you.

